@node Red Hat Linux, Microsoft Windows, , Installation from Binary Packages
@subsection Red Hat Linux
@cindex Installing, Red Hat

For Red Hat systems, apcupsd is
available in binary RPM format.  This is the simplest way to install.
If you have no previous version of apcupsd
on your machine and are creating a standalone configuration, simply
install the RPM with a normal @code{rpm -ihv} command.
You're done, and can now skip the rest of this chapter and go straight
to tweaking your run-time
configuration file. (@pxref{After Installation})

If you have a previous installation, you can upgrade with a normal
@code{rpm -Uhv}, but this may not upgrade the halt script.
It may be better to do the upgrade as a remove (@code{rpm -e})
foll;owed by a fresh install (@code{rpm -ihv}).

After installation of the binary RPM, please verify carefully
that @file{/etc/rc.d/init.d/halt} was properly updated
and contains new script lines flagged with @strong{***APCUPSD***}.

Since there is no standard location for
@file{cgi-bin}, the rpm will place the binary CGI
programs in the directory @file{/etc/apcupsd/cgi}. To
actually use them, you must copy or move them to your actual cgi-bin
directory, which on many systems is located in
@file{/home/httpd/cgi-bin}.

