@section Checking Your Configuration File
@cindex Checking Conf file

Once you have installed apcupsd, either
from a binary package or by building from source, your next step
should be to inspect your @file{/etc/apcupsd/apcupsd.conf}
file to make sure it is valid.

You can read the complete reference on configuration
directives (@pxref{Configuration Directive Reference}), but if you are setting up a normal standalone 
configuration you should only need to check (and possibly fix) the
first three items listed below.

Your UPSTYPE should be the UPS's protocol type: dumb, apcsmart,
usb, net, snmp, or ether.  Your UPSCABLE should be the type of cable you are
using.  You should have gotten both from the table of types (@pxref{type_table}); usually they will both
be the string "usb".

If you have a USB device, it is better not to specify a
DEVICE directive by commenting it out. Apcupsd will automatically 
search for your device in the standard places.
If you specify a DEVICE, it should be the name of the device (or device range)
that apcupsd is to use to communicate with
the UPS.  If you're using a USB UPS under Linux, you may leave
the device name field blank and apcupsd
will search all the standard locations for the UPS. You
may also explicitly specify the device location as
either @file{/dev/usb/hid/hiddev[0-15]} (on non-Red-Hat
systems) or @file{/dev/usb/hiddev[0-15]} (on Red Hat
systems).

Note that you should enter "/dev/usb/hiddev[0-15]" literally
as shown.  The "[0-15]" expression tells apcupsd to search all
hiddev devices until it finds a UPS. You can restrict the search to a
subset of devices by using something like "[0-4]", but keep in
mind this will limit apcupsd's ability to locate the UPS if the kernel
relocates it to a different device node, which happens occasionally during
short power failures.

If the first time you execute apcupsd, you get
a message to the effect that the Apcupsd USB driver is missing, it means
that you most likely forgot to put @emph{--enable-usb} on
your @file{./configure} command line. If you loaded        
apcupsd from an rpm file, you may have
selected the wrong one -- please ensure that the word @emph{usb}
appears in the rpm package name.

The next chapter (@pxref{Configuration Examples}) of this
manual provides you with the essential characteristics of each main type
of configuration file.  After those elements are correct, apcupsd should
run, and then it is only a matter of customization of your setup.

@node Arranging for Reboot on Power-Up, Making sure apcupsd Is Running, Checking Your Configuration File, After Installation
@section Arranging for Reboot on Power-Up
@cindex Reboot on power up
@cindex Power up, reboot

The final consideration for a automatic reboot after a full
power down is to ensure that your computer will automatically reboot
when the power is restored.

This is not the normal behavior of most computers as shipped
from the factory. Normally after the power is cut and restored, you
must explicitly press a button for the power to actually be turned
on. You can test your computer by powering it down; shutting off the
power (pull the plug); then plugging the cord back in. If your
computer immediately starts up, good. There is nothing more to
do.

If your computer does not start up, manually turn on the
power (by pressing the power on button) and enter your computer's
SETUP program (often by pressing DEL during the power up sequence;
sometimes by pressing F10). You must then find and change the
appropriate configuration parameter to permit instant power
on.

Normally, this is located under the @strong{BOOT} menu item, and will be called something
such as @strong{Restore on AC/Power Loss} or
@strong{Full-On}. The exact words will vary
according to the ROM BIOS provider. Generally you will have three
options: @strong{Last State}, @strong{Power On}, and @strong{Power
Off}. Although @strong{Last State}
should normally work, we recommend setting your computers to @strong{Power On}. This means that whenever the power is
applied they are on. The only way to shut them off is to pull the plug
or to have a special program that powers them off
(@file{/sbin/poweroff} on Linux systems).

If after making all the changes suggested above, you cannot get
your computer to automatically reboot, you might examine your halt
script (@file{/etc/rc.d/init.d/halt} in the case of
Red Hat Linux) and see if the final line that performs the halt or
reboot contains the @code{-p} option for powering down the
computer. It should not with the logic used by
apcupsd, but if it does, the
@code{-p} option could cause your computer to power off
while the UPS is still suppling power (i.e. before the UPS kills the
power).  Depending on the setting of your BIOS, it may prevent your
computer from restarting when the power returns. As already mentioned,
this should not apply, but in case of problems it is worth a
try.

@node Making sure apcupsd Is Running, , Arranging for Reboot on Power-Up, After Installation
@section Making sure apcupsd Is Running
@cindex Checking running

The simplest way to invoke  apcupsd
is from the command line by entering:

@example

/sbin/apcupsd
@end example

To do so, you must be root. However, normally, you will want
apcupsd started automatically when your
system boots. On some systems with installation support (e.g. SUSE
and Red Hat), the installation procedure will create a script file that
you will be automatically invoked when your system reboots. On other
systems, you will have to invoke apcupsd
from your @file{rc.local} script.

On Red Hat systems, this script file that automatically invokes
apcupsd on system start and stops is:
@file{/etc/rc.d/init.d/apcupsd}

To start apcupsd manually (as you
will probably do immediately following the installation), enter the
following:

@example

/etc/rc.d/init.d/apcupsd start
@end example

To understand how this file is automatically invoked at system
startup and shutdown, see the man pages for chkconfig(8).

On SUSE systems, the script file that automatically invokes
apcupsd on system start and stops is
@file{/etc/rc.d/apcupsd}

To start apcupsd manually (as you
will probably do immediately following the installation), enter the
following:

@example

/etc/rc.d/apcupsd start
@end example

Normally, when properly installed,
apcupsd will be started and stopped
automatically by your system. Unfortunately, the details are different
for each system. Below, we give the commands for selected
systems. Alternatively, there are simple
stopapcupsd and
startapcupsd scripts in the examples
directory, or you can modify one of the scripts in the distributions
directory to meet your needs.

To stop apcupsd you can do the
following:

On Red Hat systems:

@example

/etc/rc.d/init.d/apcupsd stop
@end example

On SUSE systems:

@example

/etc/rc.d/apcupsd stop
@end example

Please see the Testing Apcupsd (@pxref{Testing Apcupsd}) chapter for more   
details on insuring that apcupsd is running
properly.

