@subsection Some Cheaper Models Do Not Have Battery Charge
@cindex Problems, no Battery charge

Unfortunately, some cheaper USB models do not seem to report
BCHARGE in the apcaccess output listing, which means with a
standard conf file, your system will be immediately shutdown.
To correct this, set the BATTERYLEVEL directive in your apcupsd.conf
file to -1.

Some of these cheaper USB UPSes also do not report the Voltage. This
is annoying but does not cause the unit to malfunction.

@node Reconnection does not clean up the lockfile, Power Off [killpower] of UPS Does Not Work, Some Cheaper Models Do Not Have Battery Charge, Known Problems with USB UPSes
@subsection Reconnection does not clean up the lockfile
@cindex Problems, lock file not cleaned up

If either you disconnect the UPS or it disconnects because of
some electrical problem, it will most certainly reconnect with a
different device number. Apcupsd will detect this and reconnect
properly. However, apcupsd does not release
the old device (USB port) lock file and create a new one. This is
not too serious.

@node Power Off [killpower] of UPS Does Not Work, apcupsd Cannot Reconnect After a Reboot, Reconnection does not clean up the lockfile, Known Problems with USB UPSes
@subsection Power Off (killpower) of UPS Does Not Work
@cindex Problems, Power off
@cindex Problems, killpower

Currently (as of 3.10.6) the code to power off the UPS works
only if you have a Linux kernel version 2.4.22 or greater, or
you have applied the patches in the examples directory to your
kernel.

@node apcupsd Cannot Reconnect After a Reboot, , Power Off [killpower] of UPS Does Not Work, Known Problems with USB UPSes
@subsection apcupsd Cannot Reconnect After a Reboot
@cindex Problems, reconnect

If apcupsd does not connect to the
USB port when you reboot, it is probably the appropriate kernel
modules are not getting loaded correctly.

You can check this by bringing up your system, fiddling around
until you get apcupsd to work with the UPS,
then doing @code{cat /proc/modules} andnd save the output
some place. Then reboot your computer and before you do anything else,
do the @code{cat /proc/modules} again. Most likely you
will find some of the usb modules are missing in the second listing.

There are two solutions:

@itemize 

@item
Ensure that you have the hotplug program loaded. It should fix
the problem. This is a bit of magic, so we are not exactly sure how
it works. The rpm I (Kern) have loaded is: hotplug-2001_02_14-15

You might want to read the man page on hotplug, and it might
be necessary to @code{cp /etc/hotplug/usb.rc
/etc/init.d/hotplug} to get it fully working.

@item
You can explicitly force the appropriate usb modules to be
loaded by adding:

@example

/sbin/modprobe <missing-module-name>
@end example

in the @file{/etc/rc.d/init.d/apcupsd} script
just after the @strong{start)} case (at about
line 17). This will force the modules to be loaded before apcupsd is
invoked.
@end itemize

