7.@tab s@tab The Sensitivity to Line Quality
@item
8.@tab p@tab The Shutdown Grace Delay
@item
9.@tab q@tab The Low Battery Warning Delay
@item
10.@tab k@tab The Alarm Delay
@item
11.@tab r@tab The Wakeup Delay
@item
12.@tab E@tab The Automatic Self Test Interval
@end multitable

The first two cases (Ident and Batt date) are somewhat special
in that you tell the UPS you want to change the value, then you
supply 8 characters that are saved in the EEPROM. The last ten item
are programmed by telling the UPS that you want it to cycle to the
next permitted value.

In each case, you indicate to the UPS that you want to change
the EEPROM by first sending the appropriate query command (e.g. "c"
for the UPS ID or "u" for the Upper Transfer voltage. This command
is then immediately followed by the cycle EEPROM command or "-". In
the case of the UPS Id or the battery date, you follow the cycle
command by the eight characters that you want to put in the EEPROM.
In the case of the other ten items, there is nothing more to
enter.

The UPS will respond by "OK" and approximately 5 seconds later
by a vertical bar (|) to indicate that the EEPROM was changed.

